## Upload session flow (decided)
 
Session is created server-side at upload time, before OCR results are shown to the user.
 
```
POST /upload/session   → { session_id }   writes: { image_hash, status: pending, uid, created_at }
POST /upload/receipt   → { session_id, raw_text, extracted_items[], unresolved[], warnings[] }
POST /pantry/batch     → confirms selected items, updates session status → confirmed
```
 
- Duplicate image hashes within a time window are rejected before the user waits for OCR
- `session_id` is the lifecycle anchor: `pending → confirmed | discarded | expired`
- Item writes happen only at confirm — no double-write risk
- Pantry items written from a session carry `source: "scan"` and `source_ref: session_id`
---
 
## Abbreviation table management
 
- Seed file generated once via a single LLM call covering common US grocery chain abbreviations
- Stored as `abbreviations.json` — plain file, editable by hand, committed to the repo
- Grows passively: any line that resolves through fuzzy matching or GLM fallback is logged as a candidate pair
- Candidates are auto-promoted when GLM confidence and dictionary match score are both high
- Does not need to be comprehensive before launch — 40–60% first-pass coverage is expected and sufficient given fuzzy matching downstream
---
 
## Bugged upload detection (ship as-is)
 
The server returns a `warnings[]` field on the upload response. The client surfaces these instead of showing an empty list.
 
| Condition | Warning |
|---|---|
| `len(raw_text) < 20` | Unreadable image — could not extract text |
| `len(raw_text) > 200` and `extracted_items = []` | Text found but no ingredients matched |
| `len(extracted_items) > 30` | Unusually long result — possible hallucination |
 
These thresholds are heuristic starting points. Adjust after reviewing real session data.
 
